## Thread.Abort Migration Analysis

Your code has **four** thread-termination patterns that break on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep` + busy wait | `Stop()` | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call is interruptible
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just let the loop condition exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — log a warning.
            // In cooperative cancellation there is no force-kill equivalent.
            // If this happens, GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't honoring the token.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and honor the token.** This is the biggest risk — if it blocks on a queue or I/O without checking the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it up and `Stop()` will hang:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks indefinitely, uninterruptible
private Item GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// ✅ After — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

**2. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one. Without the filter you could mask bugs.

**3. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The class now implements `IDisposable` to clean it up.

**4. There is no force-kill equivalent.** Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation only works if every blocking call in the chain forwards the token. Audit `ProcessItem()` too — if it does long-running work, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside it.

**5. `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` was a race.** The original code sleeps 2 seconds *then* checks — `Thread.Join(timeout)` is the correct replacement because it returns as soon as the thread exits *or* the timeout elapses, whichever comes first.
